The experimental parameters including the concentration of peptide, the concentration of ATP-s and the reaction time of PKA were optimized (Fig. 3
                        ). As shown in Fig. 3A, the cathodic ECL intensities of the Au NPs/phosphorylated peptide/CS/GCE in S2O8
                        2−/O2 system increased gradually with increasing the concentration of peptide from 0 to 120μM and then leveled off, demonstrated that 120μM peptide was sufficient to modify the electrode. Thus, the optimal peptide concentration was selected at 120μM. Fig. 3B shows that ECL intensities of the biosensor enhanced greatly with increasing the ATP-s concentration and reached a maximal ECL value at 100μM in the presence of 0.5U/mL PKA, suggesting the complete phosphorylation process. Thus, 100μM was selected as optimal ATP-s concentration. The effect of the phosphorylation reaction time was also investigated (Fig. 3C). With increasing the reaction time of PKA, the ECL intensities increased quickly from 0 to 100min and then kept almost stable, showing the complete phosphorylation of peptides. Therefore, 100min was chosen as the reaction time of PKA in the subsequent experiments.

In the inhibition assay, the PKA activity was evaluated with different concentrations of PKA inhibitor ellagic acid (Fig. 5
                        ). The ECL intensity-time curves of the biosensor shows that the ECL intensity of the S2O8
                        2−–O2 system gradually decreased with the increment of the ellagic acid concentration (Fig. 5A). Fig. 5B shows that the half-maximal inhibition value (IC50) of ellagic acid was calculated to be 3.58μM (curve a), which was lower than the value reported in the literatures [31–33]. In addition, as the tyrosine kinase inhibitor but not PKA inhibitor, DRB and quercetin were used to evaluate the specificity of the ECL biosensor. The ECL intensities had no obvious change in the presence of the DRB or quercetin even at the concentration of 8μM (curves b and c), demonstrating the excellent specificity of the proposed ECL biosensor for PKA inhibitor screening.
